2572/* Inline always-inline function calls in NODE. */
2573
2574static bool
2575inline_always_inline_functions (struct cgraph_node *node)
2576{
2577 struct cgraph_edge *e;
2578 bool inlined = false;
2579
2580 for (e = node->callees; e; e = e->next_callee)
2581 {
2582 struct cgraph_node *callee = e->callee->ultimate_alias_target ();
2583 if (!DECL_DISREGARD_INLINE_LIMITS (callee->decl))
2584 continue;
2585
2586 if (e->recursive_p ())
2587 {
2588 if (dump_file)
2589 fprintf (dump_file, " Not inlining recursive call to %s.\n",
2590 e->callee->name ());
2591 e->inline_failed = CIF_RECURSIVE_INLINING;
2592 continue;
2593 }
2594
2595 if (!can_early_inline_edge_p (e))
2596 {
2597 /* Set inlined to true if the callee is marked "always_inline" but
2598 is not inlinable. This will allow flagging an error later in
2599 expand_call_inline in tree-inline.c. */
2600 if (lookup_attribute ("always_inline",
2601 DECL_ATTRIBUTES (callee->decl)) != NULL)
2602 inlined = true;
2603 continue;
2604 }
2605
2606 if (dump_file)
2607 fprintf (dump_file, " Inlining %s into %s (always_inline).\n",
2608 xstrdup_for_dump (e->callee->name ()),
2609 xstrdup_for_dump (e->caller->name ()));
2610 inline_call (e, true, NULL, NULL, false);
2611 inlined = true;
2612 }
2613 if (inlined)
2614 inline_update_overall_summary (node);
2615
2616 return inlined;
2617}
2618
2619/* Decide on the inlining. We do so in the topological order to avoid
2620 expenses on updating data structures. */
2621
2622static bool
2623early_inline_small_functions (struct cgraph_node *node)
2624{
2625 struct cgraph_edge *e;
2626 bool inlined = false;
2627
2628 for (e = node->callees; e; e = e->next_callee)
2629 {
2630 struct cgraph_node *callee = e->callee->ultimate_alias_target ();
2631 if (!inline_summaries->get (callee)->inlinable
2632 || !e->inline_failed)
2633 continue;
2634
2635 /* Do not consider functions not declared inline. */
2636 if (!DECL_DECLARED_INLINE_P (callee->decl)
2637 && !opt_for_fn (node->decl, flag_inline_small_functions)
2638 && !opt_for_fn (node->decl, flag_inline_functions))
2639 continue;
2640
2641 if (dump_file)
2642 fprintf (dump_file, "Considering inline candidate %s.\n",
2643 callee->name ());
2644
2645 if (!can_early_inline_edge_p (e))
2646 continue;
2647
2648 if (e->recursive_p ())
2649 {
2650 if (dump_file)
2651 fprintf (dump_file, " Not inlining: recursive call.\n");
2652 continue;
2653 }
2654
2655 if (!want_early_inline_function_p (e))
2656 continue;
2657
2658 if (dump_file)
2659 fprintf (dump_file, " Inlining %s into %s.\n",
2660 xstrdup_for_dump (callee->name ()),
2661 xstrdup_for_dump (e->caller->name ()));
2662 inline_call (e, true, NULL, NULL, false);
2663 inlined = true;
2664 }
2665
2666 if (inlined)
2667 inline_update_overall_summary (node);
2668
2669 return inlined;
2670}
2671
2672unsigned int
2673early_inliner (function *fun)
2674{
2675 struct cgraph_node *node = cgraph_node::get (current_function_decl);
2676 struct cgraph_edge *edge;
2677 unsigned int todo = 0;
2678 int iterations = 0;
2679 bool inlined = false;
2680
2681 if (seen_error ())
2682 return 0;
2683
2684 /* Do nothing if datastructures for ipa-inliner are already computed. This
2685 happens when some pass decides to construct new function and
2686 cgraph_add_new_function calls lowering passes and early optimization on
2687 it. This may confuse ourself when early inliner decide to inline call to
2688 function clone, because function clones don't have parameter list in
2689 ipa-prop matching their signature. */
2690 if (ipa_node_params_sum)
2691 return 0;
2692
2693 if (flag_checking)
2694 node->verify ();
2695 node->remove_all_references ();
2696
2697 /* Rebuild this reference because it dosn't depend on
2698 function's body and it's required to pass cgraph_node
2699 verification. */
2700 if (node->instrumented_version
2701 && !node->instrumentation_clone)
2702 node->create_reference (node->instrumented_version, IPA_REF_CHKP, NULL);
2703
2704 /* Even when not optimizing or not inlining inline always-inline
2705 functions. */
2706 inlined = inline_always_inline_functions (node);
2707
2708 if (!optimize
2709 || flag_no_inline
2710 || !flag_early_inlining
2711 /* Never inline regular functions into always-inline functions
2712 during incremental inlining. This sucks as functions calling
2713 always inline functions will get less optimized, but at the
2714 same time inlining of functions calling always inline
2715 function into an always inline function might introduce
2716 cycles of edges to be always inlined in the callgraph.
2717
2718 We might want to be smarter and just avoid this type of inlining. */
2719 || (DECL_DISREGARD_INLINE_LIMITS (node->decl)
2720 && lookup_attribute ("always_inline",
2721 DECL_ATTRIBUTES (node->decl))))
2722 ;
2723 else if (lookup_attribute ("flatten",
2724 DECL_ATTRIBUTES (node->decl)) != NULL)
2725 {
2726 /* When the function is marked to be flattened, recursively inline
2727 all calls in it. */
2728 if (dump_file)
2729 fprintf (dump_file,
2730 "Flattening %s\n", node->name ());
2731 flatten_function (node, true);
2732 inlined = true;
2733 }
2734 else
2735 {
2736 /* If some always_inline functions was inlined, apply the changes.
2737 This way we will not account always inline into growth limits and
2738 moreover we will inline calls from always inlines that we skipped
2739 previously because of conditional above. */
2740 if (inlined)
2741 {
2742 timevar_push (TV_INTEGRATION);
2743 todo |= optimize_inline_calls (current_function_decl);
2744 /* optimize_inline_calls call above might have introduced new
2745 statements that don't have inline parameters computed. */
2746 for (edge = node->callees; edge; edge = edge->next_callee)
2747 {
2748 if (inline_edge_summary_vec.length () > (unsigned) edge->uid)
2749 {
2750 struct inline_edge_summary *es = inline_edge_summary (edge);
2751 es->call_stmt_size
2752 = estimate_num_insns (edge->call_stmt, &eni_size_weights);
2753 es->call_stmt_time
2754 = estimate_num_insns (edge->call_stmt, &eni_time_weights);
2755 }
2756 }
2757 inline_update_overall_summary (node);
2758 inlined = false;
2759 timevar_pop (TV_INTEGRATION);
2760 }
2761 /* We iterate incremental inlining to get trivial cases of indirect
2762 inlining. */
2763 while (iterations < PARAM_VALUE (PARAM_EARLY_INLINER_MAX_ITERATIONS)
2764 && early_inline_small_functions (node))
2765 {
2766 timevar_push (TV_INTEGRATION);
2767 todo |= optimize_inline_calls (current_function_decl);
2768
2769 /* Technically we ought to recompute inline parameters so the new
2770 iteration of early inliner works as expected. We however have
2771 values approximately right and thus we only need to update edge
2772 info that might be cleared out for newly discovered edges. */
2773 for (edge = node->callees; edge; edge = edge->next_callee)
2774 {
2775 /* We have no summary for new bound store calls yet. */
2776 if (inline_edge_summary_vec.length () > (unsigned)edge->uid)
2777 {
2778 struct inline_edge_summary *es = inline_edge_summary (edge);
2779 es->call_stmt_size
2780 = estimate_num_insns (edge->call_stmt, &eni_size_weights);
2781 es->call_stmt_time
2782 = estimate_num_insns (edge->call_stmt, &eni_time_weights);
2783 }
2784 if (edge->callee->decl
2785 && !gimple_check_call_matching_types (
2786 edge->call_stmt, edge->callee->decl, false))
2787 {
2788 edge->inline_failed = CIF_MISMATCHED_ARGUMENTS;
2789 edge->call_stmt_cannot_inline_p = true;
2790 }
2791 }
2792 if (iterations < PARAM_VALUE (PARAM_EARLY_INLINER_MAX_ITERATIONS) - 1)
2793 inline_update_overall_summary (node);
2794 timevar_pop (TV_INTEGRATION);
2795 iterations++;
2796 inlined = false;
2797 }
2798 if (dump_file)
2799 fprintf (dump_file, "Iterations: %i\n", iterations);
2800 }
2801
2802 if (inlined)
2803 {
2804 timevar_push (TV_INTEGRATION);
2805 todo |= optimize_inline_calls (current_function_decl);
2806 timevar_pop (TV_INTEGRATION);
2807 }
2808
2809 fun->always_inline_functions_inlined = true;
2810
2811 return todo;
2812}
